<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="609" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="609">
The type series were collected by Roger Beaver in Brazil. The type series have field notebook codes C47, D-35, Nos. 170, 172, No. E-18 on their locality labels (
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" pagination="391 - 401" refId="B85" refString="Wood, SL, 1975b. New synonymy and new species of American bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytidae) Part II. Great Basin Naturalist 35: 391 - 401" title="New synonymy and new species of American bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytidae) Part II." volume="35" year="1975 b">Wood 1975b</bibRefCitation>
). These specimens were collected from two small cut trees of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Burseraceae" genus="Protium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Protium" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Protium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Burseraceae" genus="Protium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Burseraceae</taxonomicName>
) with stem diameters between 3.5-4.5 cm. Two gallery systems were investigated and branched rather irregularly in the transverse plane of the wood, penetrating ~2 cm deep, and were without enlargements or brood chambers (R.A. Beaver, pers. comm., 11 November 2020). Specimens were also collected by canopy fogging.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="609" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="609">
This species was omitted from 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="Brigham Young University, M. L. Bean Life Science Museum; Provo" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" refId="B91" refString="Wood, SL, 2007. Bark and ambrosia beetles of South America (Coleoptera: Scolytidae). Brigham Young University, M.L. Bean Life Science Museum; Provo" title="Bark and ambrosia beetles of South America (Coleoptera: Scolytidae)." year="2007">Wood (2007)</bibRefCitation>
. In his description 
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="Great Basin Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" pagination="391 - 401" refId="B85" refString="Wood, SL, 1975b. New synonymy and new species of American bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytidae) Part II. Great Basin Naturalist 35: 391 - 401" title="New synonymy and new species of American bark beetles (Coleoptera: Scolytidae) Part II." volume="35" year="1975 b">Wood (1975b)</bibRefCitation>
allied this species to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1975" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Curculionidae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xyleborus molestulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="molestulus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Xyleborus molestulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which he later placed in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Theoborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Theoborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Theoborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wood, SL" journalOrPublisher="The Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" pagination="1 - 1553" refId="B92" refString="Wood, SL, Bright, DE, 1992. A catalog of Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Coleoptera), part 2: Taxonomic index. The Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs 13: 1 - 1553" title="A catalog of Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Coleoptera), part 2: Taxonomic index." volume="13" year="1992">Wood and Bright 1992</bibRefCitation>
: 661) but which has recently been recognized as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schedl" baseAuthorityYear="1951" class="Hexapoda" family="Curculionidae" genus="Euwallacea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Euwallacea perbrevis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perbrevis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Euwallacea perbrevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Schedl, 1951) (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.983.52630" author="Smith, SM" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" pagination="1 - 442" refId="B76" refString="Smith, SM, Beaver, RA, Cognato, AI, 2020. A monograph of the Xyleborini (Coleoptera, Curculionidae, Scolytinae) of the Indochinese Peninsula (except Malaysia) and China. ZooKeys 983: 1 - 442, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.983.52630" title="A monograph of the Xyleborini (Coleoptera, Curculionidae, Scolytinae) of the Indochinese Peninsula (except Malaysia) and China." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.983.52630" volume="983" year="2020">Smith et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). This species shares the diagnostic characteristics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hopkins" authorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Malvaceae" genus="Coptoborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coptoborus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="609" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="609">Coptoborus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and is here transferred.
</paragraph>
